@MetaKnight964‚Äã Why is the planet warm? Because greenhouse gasses form a layer around our planet which we call the atmosphere. It traps the heat from escaping, and makes life possible on Earth. But as humans add more and more carbon to the carbon equilibrium it becomes unstable, trapping more and more heat, eventually becoming too hot to sustain life. Sea levels rise, ocean floor life is destroyed, and forest fires become commonplace. We are already seeing places being affected by the rising sea levels. It's not just the carbon equilibrium, there is also deforestation, waste, acidification of the water, using up all the natural resources etc. There are too many things to mention.
+MaXteZ There is no evidence the planet is being destroyed by humans.

The irony that your profile picture is a cat, presumably your pet cat. We treat one animal with such divine respect and yet slaughter the other. What's the difference? They both breathe, feel pain, develop connections with humans and other animals. The difference is we've grown up under the notion that your cat's life is more sacred than the lives of the hundreds of animals that end up on your plate. I mean the utmost respect in this comment. I respect everyone's choice, and of course, their opinion.¬† I for one do believe the science behind the link between our grotesquely bloated animal agriculture industry and environmental destruction.¬†

The fact people are ignorant enough to cite a documentary instead of scientific data is disturbing. Even more disturbing is the fact that, often, these claims are pushed by vegans and vegetarians who profess ethical living but are willing to fudge data. Where are the ethics?

@Belal DarkneSS¬†The most sustainable future is one where we don't waste land, water, and food on livestock, as they take up much more land than crops. Also, as you said, "terra forming" desolate lands into fertile ones. And of course we also need sustainable energy production and electric transportation. The harsh truth is that recycling once in a while and turning off your lights isn't going to have a big impact. If you want to save the planet: stop eating animal byproducts, don't drive combustion engine cars, recycle as much as you can, and don't waste energy.

@Elliot Vickers I didn't say I think they care about the planet.¬† For all I know, they're just a bunch of greedy fat cats who had some ulterior motive.¬† That's not the point I was making.¬† I was simply saying that having this climate deal is a whole lot better than not having it.¬† But let's get back to my original comment, which you clearly disagree with.¬† If you disagree with my comment "We might survive this century afterall", then you naturally agree with the opposite of the my comment, which is "We are still unlikely to survive this century".¬† I find that harder to believe than my comment.¬† My political views have almost nothing to do with my comment, but if you'd like to talk about them I'd be happy to.¬† But let me preface it by saying as long as you have one really good reason for supporting whoever you support, I won't give you crap about it.¬† I ask that you give me the same respect.¬† My number one reason I support Bernie Sanders is that he's rejecting super PACs.¬† Super PACs make up more than 60% of campaign funds, and they are inherently corrupt.¬† Even if I disagreed with everything else about Bernie (which I don't), I would still support him because he's the only candidate we can trust.¬† Everyone else will hold their tongues, make vague promises, and use overused applause lines, but only Bernie can make specific promises and deliver.¬† The whole reason politicians have a hard time getting anything done is because they have wealthy donors they answer to and want to appease.¬† Without them, a politician could finally do what he said he'd do.¬† That's why Bernie has confidently set goals like free college and infrastructure spending.¬† Because he's the only one who COULD do it.¬† Everyone else would have some dead weight holding them back.¬†

@Elliot Vickers Well I won't lie, I haven't read it myself.¬† In fact, almost no one reads the original sources for ANYTHING important.¬† For most people (myself included) we see certain sources as credible, and when they get excited for something, we do as well.¬† It's as simple as that.¬† I believe that climate change is a big deal, the sources that I trust don't particularly think it has any cheap tricks up its sleeve, so therefore, I'm optimistic.¬† I feel like that's a reasonable opinion.¬† No need to call me retarded.¬†

@MetaKnight964 Ah, well with that comment, you've lost all credibility in my eyes as well, so there's not really any point in discussing it.¬† On the other hand, if you'd like to have a real discussion about why I believe climate change is real and man-made, then we can talk
